# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sigstore-signing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] The project is backed by the Open Source Security Foundation (OpenSSF) under the Linux Foundation, with contributions from Google, Red Hat, Chainguard, GitHub and Purdue University.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] It is 100% open source and free to use for all developers and software providers.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] The Sigstore community develops and maintains tools to simplify code signing and verification, and also operates a public-good, non-profit service to improve the open source software supply chain.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] Digital signatures are a way to verify the authenticity of a software artifact.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] Software consumers can trace software back to the source to know who created the artifact and that it has not been altered or tampered with after it was signed.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] Traditional artifact signing relies on exchanging cryptographic keypairs for signature verification.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] The software creator keeps one key secret (the private “signing” key) and publishes the other (the public “verification” key).
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] When a software consumer wants to verify an artifact’s signature, the verification keys are exchanged to prove that the holder of the private key created the signature.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] Sigstore addresses these problems by helping users move away from a key-based signing approach to an identity-based one.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] The signer ideally forgoes using long-lived keypairs.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] With “keyless” or “ephemeral key” signing, users verify the artifact using the transparency log for signature verification rather than keys.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] A Sigstore client, such as Cosign, creates a public/private key pair and makes a certificate signing request to our code-signing certificate authority (Fulcio) with the public key.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] A verifiable OpenID Connect (OIDC) identity token is also provided in the request.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] The OIDC token contains a user’s email address or service account, or workflow information in the case of CI signing.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] The certificate authority verifies this token and issues a short-lived certificate bound to the provided identity and public key.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] You don’t have to manage signing keys, and Sigstore services never obtain your private key.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] The public key that a Sigstore client creates gets bound to the issued certificate, and the private key is discarded after a single signing.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] After the client signs the artifact, the artifact’s digest, signature and certificate are persisted in a transparency log: an immutable, append-only ledger known as Rekor.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] With this log, signing events can be publicly audited.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] Identity owners can monitor the log to verify that their identity is being properly used, and someone who downloads an artifact can confirm that the certificate was valid at the time of signing.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] Together, verification of this information tells the user that the artifact comes from its expected source and has not been tampered with after its creation.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] For more information on the modules that make up Sigstore, review Tooling.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] To use Sigstore, you must first install the client.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] You can then pick the subject matter you wish to learn about from the menu items on the left.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] Up to date documentation, best practices, and detailed scenarios for Sigstore live here.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] These pages are maintained by the community and intended to help anyone get set up with any of the technologies, to find what you’re looking for fast.
[src:sigstore-signing/about-overview] It’s also where we keep all the relevant pages for the Sigstore trust root, from signing ceremonies to security practices.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Certificate Transparency makes public all issued certificates in the form of a distributed ledger, giving website owners and auditors the ability to detect and expose inappropriately issued certificates.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Work on Certificate Transparency first began in 2011 after the certificate authority DigiNotar became compromised and started issuing malicious certificates.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Google engineers submitted a draft to the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) in 2012.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] This effort resulted in IETF RFC 6962, a standard defining a system of public logs to record all certificates issued by publicly trusted certificate authorities, allowing efficient identification of mistakenly or maliciously issued certificates.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] The certificate transparency system consists of a system of append-only certificate logs.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Logs are operated by many parties, including browser vendors and certificate authorities.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Certificates that support certificate transparency must include one or more *signed certificate timestamps* (SCTs), which is a promise from a log operator to include the certificate in their log within a *maximum merge delay* (MMD).
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] At some point within the maximum merge delay, the log operator adds the certificate to their log.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Each entry in a log references the hash of a previous one, forming a Merkle tree.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] The *signed tree head* (STH) references the current root of the Merkle tree.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] The CA issues a special *precertificate*, a certificate which carries a poison extension signaling that it should not be accepted by user agents.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] The CA sends the precertificate to logs.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Logs return corresponding SCTs to the CA.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] The CA attaches SCTs collected from logs as an X.509 extension to the final certificate and provides it to the applicant.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Finally, the CA may decide to log the final certificate as well.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Let's Encrypt E1 CA, for example, logs both precertificates and final certificates (see CA crt.sh profile page under 'issued certificates' section), whereas Google GTS CA 2A1 does not (see crt.sh profile page).
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Due to the large quantities of certificates issued with the Web PKI, certificate transparency logs can grow to contain many certificates.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] This large quantity of certificates can cause strain on logs.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Temporal sharding is a method to reduce the strain on logs by sharding a log into multiple logs, and having each shard only accept precertificates and certificates with an expiration date in a particular time period (usually a calendar year).
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Cloudflare's Nimbus series of logs was the first to use temporal sharding.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] One of the problems with digital certificate management is that fraudulent certificates take a long time to be spotted, reported and revoked.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] An issued certificate not logged using Certificate Transparency may never be spotted at all.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] The main advantage with Certificate Transparency is the ability for cyber security teams to defend companies and organisations by monitoring for suspicious domains registering certificates.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] The new certificates for these suspicious domains may have similar names to other legitimate domains and are designed to be used to support malicious activities such as phishing attacks.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Certificate Transparency puts cyber security teams in control and enables them to issue domain take down orders for suspicious domains and allows them to apply cyber security controls on web proxies and email gateways for immediate protection.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Domain names that are used on internal networks and have certificates issued by certificate authorities become publicly searchable as their certificates are added to CT logs.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Certificate Transparency depends on verifiable Certificate Transparency logs.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] A log appends new certificates to an ever-growing Merkle hash tree.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] A log may accept certificates that are not yet fully valid and certificates that have expired.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] There are two primary categories of monitors: log integrity monitors (also referred to as log verifiers or log auditors) and tracking monitors.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Some companies offering monitoring services collect data from all logs and provide paid services for domain tracking.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] For example, a domain owner can register for Cloudflare's services, which globally monitor all logs and send email updates whenever a certificate is issued for their domain, allowing them control over all certificates issued.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Large organizations can maintain their own monitors, which continuously scan for new certificate issued for their domains.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] If a certificate authority (CA) attempts to issue a "bad" certificate for one of these domains (intentionally or unintentionally), the monitor will quickly detect it.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Two popular APIs for research and tracking are Sectigo's crt.sh and Cloudflare MerkleTown.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] These tools facilitate the monitoring of certificate issuance and help organizations stay on top of the security of their domains.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] While there is an additional consideration of monitoring the monitors themselves, the likelihood of a significant impact on system performance or security due to misbehavior of a single monitor is low.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] This is because there are numerous log monitors, providing a layered approach to security and minimizing the risk of a single point of failure.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Apple and Google have separate log programs with distinct policies and lists of trusted logs.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Certificate Transparency logs maintain their own root stores and only accept certificates that chain back to the trusted roots.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] A number of misbehaving logs have been publishing inconsistent root stores in the past.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] A new structure for logs is based on dividing the Merkle Tree into tiles.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] This structure is expected to be faster, easier to operate, and to provide much smaller merge delays (the current Maximum Merge Delay is 24 hours).
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Chrome has updated its Certificate Transparency (CT) policy to accept SCTs from the new static-CT-API logs only if an SCT from an RFC 6962 log is also present, and it intends to complete the migration to static-CT-API CT logs by the end of 2025.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] In 2011, a reseller of the certificate authority Comodo was attacked and the certificate authority DigiNotar was compromised, demonstrating existing flaws in the certificate authority ecosystem and prompting work on various mechanisms to prevent or monitor unauthorized certificate issuance.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Google employees Ben Laurie, Adam Langley and Emilia Kasper began work on an open source framework for detecting mis-issued certificates the same year.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] In 2012, they submitted the first draft of the standard to IETF under the code-name "Sunlight".
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] In March 2013, Google launched its first certificate transparency log.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] In June 2013, RFC 6962 "Certificate Transparency" was published, based on the 2012 draft.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] In September 2013, DigiCert became the first certificate authority to implement Certificate Transparency.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] In 2015, Google Chrome began requiring Certificate Transparency for newly issued Extended Validation Certificates.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] It began requiring Certificate Transparency for all certificates newly issued by Symantec from June 1, 2016, after they were found to have issued 187 certificates without the domain owners' knowledge.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Since April 2018, this requirement has been extended to all certificates.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] On March 23, 2018, Cloudflare announced its own CT log named *Nimbus*.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] In May 2019, certificate authority Let's Encrypt launched its own CT log called Oak.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Since February 2020, it is included in approved log lists and is usable by all publicly trusted certificate authorities.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] In December 2021, RFC 9162 "Certificate Transparency Version 2.0" was published.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] Version 2.0 includes major changes to the required structure of the log certificate, as well as support for Ed25519 as a signature algorithm of SCTs and support for including certificate inclusion proofs with the SCT.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] However, it has not seen industry adoption and is considered dead on arrival.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] In February 2022, Google published an update to their CT policy, which removes the requirement for certificates to include a SCT from their own CT log service, matching all the requirements for certificates to those previously published by Apple.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] In February 2025, Mozilla Firefox desktop version 135 began requiring Certificate Transparency for all certificates issued by a certificate authority in Mozilla's Root CA Program.
[src:sigstore-signing/certificate-transparency] In Certificate Transparency Version 2.0, a log must use one of the algorithms in the IANA registry "Signature Algorithms".
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Code signing can provide several valuable features.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] The most common use of code signing is to provide security when deploying; in some programming languages, it can also be used to help prevent namespace conflicts.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Almost every code signing implementation will provide some sort of digital signature mechanism to verify the identity of the author or build system, and a checksum to verify that the object has not been modified.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] It can also be used to provide versioning information about an object or to store other metadata about an object.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] The efficacy of code signing as an authentication mechanism for software depends on the security of underpinning signing keys.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] As with other public key infrastructure (PKI) technologies, the integrity of the system relies on publishers securing their private keys against unauthorized access.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Keys stored in software on general-purpose computers are susceptible to compromise.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Therefore, it is more secure, and best practice, to store keys in secure, tamper-proof, cryptographic hardware devices known as hardware security modules or HSMs.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Many code signing implementations will provide a way to sign the code using a system involving a pair of keys, one public and one private, similar to the process employed by TLS or SSH.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] For example, in the case of .NET, the developer uses a private key to sign their libraries or executables each time they build.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] This key will be unique to a developer or group or sometimes per application or object.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] The developer can either generate this key on their own or obtain one from a trusted certificate authority (CA).
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Code signing is particularly valuable in distributed environments, where the source of a given piece of code may not be immediately evident - for example Java applets, ActiveX controls and other active web and browser scripting code.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Another important usage is to safely provide updates and patches to existing software.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Windows, Mac OS X, and most Linux distributions provide updates using code signing to ensure that it is not possible for others to maliciously distribute code via the patch system.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] It allows the receiving operating system to verify that the update is legitimate, even if the update was delivered by third parties or physical media (disks).
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Code signing is used on Windows and Mac OS X to authenticate software on first run, ensuring that the software has not been maliciously tampered with by a third-party distributor or download site.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Debian-based Linux distributions (among others) validate downloaded packages using public key cryptography.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] The public key used to authenticate the code signature should be traceable back to a trusted root authority CA, preferably using a secure public key infrastructure (PKI).
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] This does not ensure that the code itself can be trusted, only that it comes from the stated source (or more explicitly, from a particular private key).
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] A CA provides a root trust level and is able to assign trust to others by proxy.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] If a user trusts a CA, then the user can presumably trust the legitimacy of code that is signed with a key generated by that CA or one of its proxies.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Many operating systems and frameworks contain built-in trust for one or more certification authorities.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] It is also commonplace for large organizations to implement a private CA, internal to the organization, which provides the same features as public CAs, but it is only trusted within the organization.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Extended validation (EV) code signing certificates are subject to additional validation and technical requirements.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] These guidelines are based on the CA/B Forum's Baseline Requirements and Extended Validation Guidelines.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Certain applications, such as signing Windows 10 kernel-mode drivers, require an EV code signing certificate.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] This is an example of a decoded EV code signing certificate used by SSL.com to sign software.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] `SSL.com EV Code Signing Intermediate CA RSA R3` is shown as the Issuer's commonName, identifying this as an EV code signing certificate.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] The certificate's `Subject` field describes SSL Corp as an organization.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] `Code Signing` is shown as the sole X509v3 Extended Key Usage.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] The other model is the trust on first use model, in which developers can choose to provide their own self-generated key.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] In this scenario, the user would normally have to obtain the public key in some fashion directly from the developer to verify the object is from them for the first time.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Many code signing systems will store the public key inside the signature.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Some software frameworks and OSs that check the code's signature before executing will allow you to choose to trust that developer from that point on after the first run.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] An application developer can provide a similar system by including the public keys with the installer.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] The key can then be used to ensure that any subsequent objects that need to run, such as upgrades, plugins, or another application, are all verified as coming from that same developer.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Time-stamping was designed to circumvent the trust warning that will appear in the case of an expired certificate.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] In effect, time-stamping extends the code trust beyond the validity period of a certificate.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] In the event that a certificate has to be revoked due to a compromise, a specific date and time of the compromising event will become part of the revocation record.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] In this case, time-stamping helps establish whether the code was signed before or after the certificate was compromised.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Developers need to sign their iOS and tvOS apps before running them on any real device and before uploading them to the App Store.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] This is needed to prove that the developer owns a valid Apple Developer ID.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] An application needs a valid profile or certificate so that it can run on the devices.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Like any security measure, code signing can be defeated.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Users can be tricked into running unsigned code, or even into running code that refuses to validate, and the system only remains secure as long as the private key remains private.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] It is also important to note that code signing does not protect the end user from any malicious activity or unintentional software bugs by the software author — it merely ensures that the software has not been modified by anyone other than the author.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Sometimes, sandbox systems do not accept certificates, because of a false time-stamp or because of an excess usage of RAM.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Microsoft implements a form of code signing (based on Authenticode) provided for Microsoft tested drivers.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Since drivers run in the kernel, they can destabilize the system or open the system to security holes.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] For this reason, Microsoft tests drivers submitted to its WHQL program.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] After the driver has passed, Microsoft signs that version of the driver as being safe.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] On 32-bit systems only, installing drivers that are not validated with Microsoft is possible after agreeing to allow the installation at a prompt warning the user that the code is unsigned.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] For .NET (managed) code, there is an additional mechanism called Strong Name Signing that uses Public/Private keys and SHA-1 hash as opposed to certificates.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] However, Microsoft discourages reliance on Strong Name Signing as a replacement for Authenticode.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] The CAs subsequently issued announcements on compliance with the decision.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] In the context of consumer devices such as games consoles, the term "unsigned code" is often used to refer to an application which has not been signed with the cryptographic key normally required for software to be accepted and executed.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] Most console games have to be signed with a secret key designed by the console maker or the game will not load on the console (both to enforce Vendor lock-in and combat software piracy).
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] There are several methods to get unsigned code to execute which include software exploits, the use of a modchip, a technique known as the swap trick or running a softmod.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] It may not initially seem obvious why simply copying a signed application onto another DVD does not allow it to boot.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] On the Xbox, the reason for this is that the Xbox executable file (XBE) contains a media-type flag, which specifies the type of media that the XBE is bootable from.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] On nearly all Xbox software, this is set such that the executable will only boot from factory-produced discs, so simply copying the executable to burnable media is enough to stop the execution of the software.
[src:sigstore-signing/code-signing] However, since the executable is signed, simply changing the value of the flag is not possible as this alters the signature of the executable, causing it to fail validation when checked.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] A **digital signature** is a mathematical scheme for verifying the authenticity of digital messages or documents.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] A valid digital signature on a message gives a recipient confidence that the message came from a sender known to the recipient.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Digital signatures are a type of public-key cryptography, and are commonly used for software distribution, financial transactions, contract management software, and in other cases where it is important to detect forgery or tampering.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Digital signatures are often used to implement electronic signatures, which include any electronic data that carries the intent of a signature, but not all electronic signatures use digital signatures.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] *Security* (existential unforgeability under chosen-message attack, or EUF-CMA): It should be computationally infeasible to generate a valid signature for a party without knowing that party's private key.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Here 1*n* refers to a unary number in the formalism of computational complexity theory.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] where *A**S*(*sk*, · ) denotes that *A* has access to the oracle, *S*(*sk*, · ), *Q* denotes the set of the queries on *S* made by *A*, which knows the public key, *pk*, and the security parameter, *n*, and *x* ∉ *Q* denotes that the adversary may not directly query the string, *x*, on *S*.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] In 1976, Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman first described the notion of a digital signature scheme, although they only conjectured that such schemes existed based on functions that are trapdoor one-way permutations.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Soon afterwards, Ronald Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Len Adleman invented the RSA algorithm, which could be used to produce primitive digital signatures (although only as a proof-of-concept – "plain" RSA signatures are not secure).
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] The first widely marketed software package to offer digital signature was Lotus Notes 1.0, released in 1989, which used the RSA algorithm.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Other digital signature schemes were soon developed after RSA, the earliest being Lamport signatures, Merkle signatures (also known as "Merkle trees" or simply "Hash trees"), and Rabin signatures.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] In 1988, Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali, and Ronald Rivest became the first to rigorously define the security requirements of digital signature schemes.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] They described a hierarchy of attack models for signature schemes, and also presented the GMR signature scheme, the first that could be proved to prevent even an existential forgery against a chosen message attack, which is the currently accepted security definition for signature schemes.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] The first such scheme which is not built on trapdoor functions but rather on a family of function with a much weaker required property of one-way permutation was presented by Moni Naor and Moti Yung.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] One digital signature scheme (of many) is based on RSA.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] To create signature keys, generate an RSA key pair containing a modulus, *N*, that is the product of two random secret distinct large primes, along with integers, *e* and *d*, such that *e* *d* ≡ 1 (mod *φ*(*N*)), where *φ* is Euler's totient function.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] The signer's public key consists of *N* and *e*, and the signer's secret key contains *d*.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Used directly, this type of signature scheme is vulnerable to key-only existential forgery attack.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] To create a forgery, the attacker picks a random signature σ and uses the verification procedure to determine the message, *m*, corresponding to that signature.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] In practice, however, this type of signature is not used directly, but rather, the message to be signed is first hashed to produce a short digest, that is then padded to larger width comparable to *N*, then signed with the reverse trapdoor function.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] This forgery attack, then, only produces the padded hash function output that corresponds to σ, but not a message that leads to that value, which does not lead to an attack.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] In the random oracle model, hash-then-sign (an idealized version of that practice where hash and padding combined have close to *N* possible outputs), this form of signature is existentially unforgeable, even against a chosen-plaintext attack.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] There are several reasons to sign such a hash (or message digest) instead of the whole document.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] The signature will be much shorter and thus save time since hashing is generally much faster than signing in practice.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] A hash function can be used to convert an arbitrary input into the proper format.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Without the hash function, the text "to be signed" may have to be split (separated) in blocks small enough for the signature scheme to act on them directly.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] However, the receiver of the signed blocks is not able to recognize if all the blocks are present and in the appropriate order.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] As organizations move away from paper documents with ink signatures or authenticity stamps, digital signatures can provide added assurances of the evidence to provenance, identity, and status of an electronic document as well as acknowledging informed consent and approval by a signatory.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] The United States Government Printing Office (GPO) publishes electronic versions of the budget, public and private laws, and congressional bills with digital signatures.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Universities including Penn State, University of Chicago, and Stanford are publishing electronic student transcripts with digital signatures.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] A message may have letterhead or a handwritten signature identifying its sender, but letterheads and handwritten signatures can be copied and pasted onto forged messages.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Even legitimate messages may be modified in transit.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] With a digital signature scheme, the central office can arrange beforehand to have a public key on file whose private key is known only to the branch office.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] The branch office can later sign a message and the central office can use the public key to verify the signed message was not a forgery before acting on it.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] A forger who *doesn't* know the sender's private key can't sign a different message, or even change a single digit in an existing message without making the recipient's signature verification fail.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Non-repudiation, or more specifically non-repudiation of origin, is an important aspect of digital signatures.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] By this property, an entity that has signed some information cannot at a later time deny having signed it.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Similarly, access to the public key only does not enable a fraudulent party to fake a valid signature.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Note that these authentication, non-repudiation etc. properties rely on the secret key *not having been revoked* prior to its usage.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Public revocation of a key-pair is a required ability, else leaked secret keys would continue to implicate the claimed owner of the key-pair.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Checking revocation status requires an "online" check; e.g., checking a certificate revocation list or via the Online Certificate Status Protocol.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Very roughly this is analogous to a vendor who receives credit-cards first checking online with the credit-card issuer to find if a given card has been reported lost or stolen.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Of course, with stolen key pairs, the theft is often discovered only after the secret key's use, e.g., to sign a bogus certificate for espionage purpose.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] In a *known message* attack, the attacker is given valid signatures for a variety of messages known by the attacker but not chosen by the attacker.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] In an *adaptive chosen message* attack, the attacker first learns signatures on arbitrary messages of the attacker's choice.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] A universal forgery attack results in the ability to forge signatures for any message.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] A selective forgery attack results in a signature on a message of the adversary's choice.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] An existential forgery merely results in some valid message/signature pair not already known to the adversary.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] The strongest notion of security, therefore, is security against existential forgery under an adaptive chosen message attack.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] All public key / private key cryptosystems depend entirely on keeping the private key secret.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] A more secure alternative is to store the private key on a smart card.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Many smart cards are designed to be tamper-resistant (although some designs have been broken, notably by Ross Anderson and his students).
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] In a typical digital signature implementation, the hash calculated from the document is sent to the smart card, whose CPU signs the hash using the stored private key of the user, and then returns the signed hash.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Typically, a user must activate their smart card by entering a personal identification number or PIN code (thus providing two-factor authentication).
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] It can be arranged that the private key never leaves the smart card, although this is not always implemented.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] If the smart card is stolen, the thief will still need the PIN code to generate a digital signature.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] This reduces the security of the scheme to that of the PIN system, although it still requires an attacker to possess the card.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] A mitigating factor is that private keys, if generated and stored on smart cards, are usually regarded as difficult to copy, and are assumed to exist in exactly one copy.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Thus, the loss of the smart card may be detected by the owner and the corresponding certificate can be immediately revoked.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Private keys that are protected by software only may be easier to copy, and such compromises are far more difficult to detect.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Entering a PIN code to activate the smart card commonly requires a numeric keypad.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Some card readers have their own numeric keypad.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] This is safer than using a card reader integrated into a PC, and then entering the PIN using that computer's keyboard.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Readers with a numeric keypad are meant to circumvent the eavesdropping threat where the computer might be running a keystroke logger, potentially compromising the PIN code.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Specialized card readers are also less vulnerable to tampering with their software or hardware and are often EAL3 certified.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Smart card design is an active field, and there are smart card schemes which are intended to avoid these particular problems, despite having few security proofs so far.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a digital signature and a written signature is that the user does not "see" what they sign.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] The user application presents a hash code to be signed by the digital signing algorithm using the private key.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] An attacker who gains control of the user's PC can possibly replace the user application with a foreign substitute, in effect replacing the user's own communications with those of the attacker.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] This could allow a malicious application to trick a user into signing any document by displaying the user's original on-screen, but presenting the attacker's own documents to the signing application.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] To protect against this scenario, an authentication system can be set up between the user's application (word processor, email client, etc.) and the signing application.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] The general idea is to provide some means for both the user application and signing application to verify each other's integrity.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] For example, the signing application may require all requests to come from digitally signed binaries.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a cloud based digital signature service and a locally provided one is risk.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Many risk averse companies, including governments, financial and medical institutions, and payment processors require more secure standards, like FIPS 140-2 level 3 and FIPS 201 certification, to ensure the signature is validated and secure.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Technically speaking, a digital signature applies to a string of bits, whereas humans and applications "believe" that they sign the semantic interpretation of those bits.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] In order to be semantically interpreted, the bit string must be transformed into a form that is meaningful for humans and applications, and this is done through a combination of hardware and software based processes on a computer system.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] The problem is that the semantic interpretation of bits can change as a function of the processes used to transform the bits into semantic content.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] It is relatively easy to change the interpretation of a digital document by implementing changes on the computer system where the document is being processed.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] From a semantic perspective this creates uncertainty about what exactly has been signed.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] WYSIWYS (What You See Is What You Sign) means that the semantic interpretation of a signed message cannot be changed.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] In particular this also means that a message cannot contain hidden information that the signer is unaware of, and that can be revealed after the signature has been applied.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] WYSIWYS is a requirement for the validity of digital signatures, but this requirement is difficult to guarantee because of the increasing complexity of modern computer systems.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] The term WYSIWYS was coined by Peter Landrock and Torben Pedersen to describe some of the principles in delivering secure and legally binding digital signatures for Pan-European projects.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Digital signatures cryptographically bind an electronic identity to an electronic document and the digital signature cannot be copied to another document.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Paper contracts sometimes have the ink signature block on the last page, and the previous pages may be replaced after a signature is applied.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Digital signatures can be applied to an entire document, such that the digital signature on the last page will indicate tampering if any data on any of the pages have been altered, but this can also be achieved by signing with ink and numbering all pages of the contract.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Quality implementations: An implementation of a good algorithm (or protocol) with mistake(s) will not work.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Users (and their software) must carry out the signature protocol properly.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] The private key must remain private: If the private key becomes known to any other party, that party can produce *perfect* digital signatures of anything.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] The public key owner must be verifiable: A public key associated with Bob actually came from Bob.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] This is commonly done using a public key infrastructure (PKI) and the public key↔user association is attested by the operator of the PKI (called a certificate authority).
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] For 'open' PKIs in which anyone can request such an attestation (universally embodied in a cryptographically protected public key certificate), the possibility of mistaken attestation is non-trivial.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Commercial PKI operators have suffered several publicly known problems.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Such mistakes could lead to falsely signed, and thus wrongly attributed, documents.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] 'Closed' PKI systems are more expensive, but less easily subverted in this way.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Only if all of these conditions are met will a digital signature actually be any evidence of who sent the message, and therefore of their assent to its contents.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Legal enactment cannot change this reality of the existing engineering possibilities, though some such have not reflected this actuality.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] The first appears to have been in Utah in the United States, followed closely by the states Massachusetts and California.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Other countries have also passed statutes or issued regulations in this area as well and the UN has had an active model law project for some time.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Adoption of technical standards for digital signatures have lagged behind much of the legislation, delaying a more or less unified engineering position on interoperability, algorithm choice, key lengths, and so on what the engineering is attempting to provide.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Some industries have established common interoperability standards for the use of digital signatures between members of the industry and with regulators.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] These include the Automotive Network Exchange for the automobile industry and the SAFE-BioPharma Association for the healthcare industry.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] In several countries, a digital signature has a status somewhat like that of a traditional pen and paper signature, as in the 1999 EU digital signature directive and 2014 EU follow-on legislation.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Generally, these provisions mean that anything digitally signed legally binds the signer of the document to the terms therein.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] For that reason, it is often thought best to use separate key pairs for encrypting and signing.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Using the encryption key pair, a person can engage in an encrypted conversation (e.g., regarding a real estate transaction), but the encryption does not legally sign every message he or she sends.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Only when both parties come to an agreement do they sign a contract with their signing keys, and only then are they legally bound by the terms of a specific document.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] After signing, the document can be sent over the encrypted link.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] If a signing key is lost or compromised, it can be revoked to mitigate any future transactions.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] If an encryption key is lost, a backup or key escrow should be utilized to continue viewing encrypted content.
[src:sigstore-signing/digital-signature] Signing keys should never be backed up or escrowed unless the backup destination is securely encrypted.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] A **public key infrastructure** (**PKI**) is a set of roles, policies, hardware, software and procedures used to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key cryptography set-ups.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] In cryptography, a PKI is an arrangement that *binds* public keys with respective identities of entities (like people and organizations).
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] The binding is established through a process of registration and issuance of certificates at and by a certificate authority (CA).
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Depending on the assurance level of the binding, this may be carried out by an automated process or under human supervision.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] When done over a network, this requires using a secure certificate enrollment or certificate management protocol such as CMP.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] The PKI role that may be delegated by a CA to assure valid and correct registration is called a *registration authority* (RA).
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] An RA is responsible for accepting requests for digital certificates and authenticating the entity making the request.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] RAs, however, do not sign or issue certificates (i.e., an RA is delegated certain tasks on behalf of a CA)." While Microsoft may have referred to a subordinate CA as an RA, this is incorrect according to the X.509 PKI standards.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] RAs do not have the signing authority of a CA and only manage the vetting and provisioning of certificates.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] In the case of Microsoft Standalone CAs, the function of RA does not exist since all of the procedures controlling the CA are based on the administration and access procedure associated with the system hosting the CA and the CA itself rather than Active Directory.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Most non-Microsoft commercial PKI solutions offer a stand-alone RA component.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] An entity must be uniquely identifiable within each CA domain on the basis of information about that entity.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] A third-party validation authority (VA) can provide this entity information on behalf of the CA.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] The X.509 standard defines the most commonly used format for public key certificates.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] PKI provides "trust services" - in plain terms trusting the actions or outputs of entities, be they people or computers.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Trust service objectives respect one or more of the following capabilities: Confidentiality, Integrity and Authenticity (CIA).
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Public-key cryptography is a cryptographic technique that enables entities to securely communicate on an insecure public network, and reliably verify the identity of an entity via digital signatures.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] A public key infrastructure (PKI) is a system for the creation, storage, and distribution of digital certificates, which are used to verify that a particular public key belongs to a certain entity.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] The PKI creates digital certificates that map public keys to entities, securely stores these certificates in a central repository and revokes them if needed.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] The primary role of the CA is to digitally sign and publish the public key bound to a given user.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] This is done using the CA's own private key, so that trust in the user key relies on one's trust in the validity of the CA's key.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] When the CA is a third party separate from the user and the system, then it is called the Registration Authority (RA), which may or may not be separate from the CA.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] The key-to-user binding is established, depending on the level of assurance the binding has, by software or under human supervision.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] The term trusted third party (TTP) may also be used for certificate authority (CA).
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Moreover, PKI is itself often used as a synonym for a CA implementation.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, which signals that it is no longer valid.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or mis-issued certificate until expiry.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Hence, revocation is an important part of a public key infrastructure.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Revocation is performed by the issuing certificate authority, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] For distributing revocation information to clients, timeliness of the discovery of revocation (and hence the window for an attacker to exploit a compromised certificate) trades off against resource usage in querying revocation statuses and privacy concerns.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] If revocation information is unavailable (either due to accident or an attack), clients must decide whether to *fail-hard* and treat a certificate as if it is revoked (and so degrade availability) or to *fail-soft* and treat it as unrevoked (and allow attackers to sidestep revocation).
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Due to the cost of revocation checks and the availability impact from potentially-unreliable remote services, Web browsers limit the revocation checks they will perform, and will fail-soft where they do.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Certificate revocation lists are too bandwidth-costly for routine use, and the Online Certificate Status Protocol presents connection latency and privacy issues.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Other schemes have been proposed but have not yet been successfully deployed to enable fail-hard checking.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] In this model of trust relationships, a CA is a trusted third party – trusted both by the subject (owner) of the certificate and by the party relying upon the certificate.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] The top spot has been held by Symantec (or VeriSign before it was purchased by Symantec) ever since [our] survey began, with it currently accounting for just under a third of all certificates.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Following major issues in how certificate issuing was managed, all major players gradually distrusted Symantec-issued certificates, starting in 2017 and completed in 2021.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] This approach involves a server that acts as an offline certificate authority within a single sign-on system.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] A single sign-on server will issue digital certificates into the client system, but never stores them.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Users can execute programs, etc. with the temporary certificate.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] It is common to find this solution variety with X.509-based certificates.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Starting Sep 2020, TLS Certificate Validity reduced to 13 Months.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] An alternative approach to the problem of public authentication of public key information is the web-of-trust scheme, which uses self-signed certificates and third-party attestations of those certificates.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] The singular term "web of trust" does not imply the existence of a single web of trust, or common point of trust, but rather one of any number of potentially disjoint "webs of trust".
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Examples of implementations of this approach are PGP (Pretty Good Privacy) and GnuPG (an implementation of OpenPGP, the standardized specification of PGP).
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Because PGP and implementations allow the use of e-mail digital signatures for self-publication of public key information, it is relatively easy to implement one's own web of trust.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] One of the benefits of the web of trust, such as in PGP, is that it can interoperate with a PKI CA fully trusted by all parties in a domain (such as an internal CA in a company) that is willing to guarantee certificates, as a trusted introducer.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] If the "web of trust" is completely trusted then, because of the nature of a web of trust, trusting one certificate is granting trust to all the certificates in that web.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] A PKI is only as valuable as the standards and practices that control the issuance of certificates and including PGP or a personally instituted web of trust could significantly degrade the trustworthiness of that enterprise's or domain's implementation of PKI.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Another alternative, which does not deal with public authentication of public key information, is the simple public key infrastructure (SPKI), which grew out of three independent efforts to overcome the complexities of X.509 and PGP's web of trust.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] SPKI does not associate users with persons, since the *key* is what is trusted, rather than the person.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] SPKI does not use any notion of trust, as the verifier is also the issuer.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] This is called an "authorization loop" in SPKI terminology, where authorization is integral to its design.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] This type of PKI is specially useful for making integrations of PKI that do not rely on third parties for certificate authorization, certificate information, etc.; a good example of this is an air-gapped network in an office.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Decentralized identifiers (DIDs) eliminate dependence on centralized registries for identifiers as well as centralized certificate authorities for key management, which is the standard in hierarchical PKI.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] In cases where the DID registry is a distributed ledger, each entity can serve as its own root authority.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] This architecture is referred to as decentralized PKI (DPKI).
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Developments in PKI occurred in the early 1970s at the British intelligence agency GCHQ, where James Ellis, Clifford Cocks and others made important discoveries related to encryption algorithms and key distribution.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Because developments at GCHQ are highly classified, the results of this work were kept secret and not publicly acknowledged until the mid-1990s.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] The public disclosure of both secure key exchange and asymmetric key algorithms in 1976 by Diffie, Hellman, Rivest, Shamir, and Adleman changed secure communications entirely.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Assorted cryptographic protocols were invented and analyzed within which the new cryptographic primitives could be effectively used.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] With the invention of the World Wide Web and its rapid spread, the need for authentication and secure communication became still more acute.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Commercial reasons alone (e.g., e-commerce, online access to proprietary databases from web browsers) were sufficient.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Taher Elgamal and others at Netscape developed the SSL protocol ('https' in Web URLs); it included key establishment, server authentication (prior to v3, one-way only), and so on.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] A PKI structure was thus created for Web users/sites wishing secure communications.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Vendors and entrepreneurs saw the possibility of a large market, started companies (or new projects at existing companies), and began to agitate for legal recognition and protection from liability.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Consumer groups raised questions about privacy, access, and liability considerations, which were more taken into consideration in some jurisdictions than in others.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] The enacted laws and regulations differed, and there were technical and operational problems in converting PKI schemes into successful commercial operation.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Progress has been much slower than pioneers had imagined it would be.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] By the first few years of the 21st century, the underlying cryptographic engineering was clearly not easy to deploy correctly.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Operating procedures (manual or automatic) were not easy to correctly design (nor even if so designed, to execute perfectly, which the engineering required).
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] The standards that existed were insufficient.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] PKI vendors have found a market, but it is not quite the market envisioned in the mid-1990s, and it has grown both more slowly and in somewhat different ways than were anticipated.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] PKIs have not solved some of the problems they were expected to, and several major vendors have gone out of business or been acquired by others.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] PKI has had the most success in government implementations; the largest PKI implementation to date is the Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) PKI infrastructure for the Common Access Cards program.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Some argue that purchasing certificates for securing websites by SSL/TLS and securing software by code signing is a costly venture for small businesses.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] However, the emergence of free alternatives, such as Let's Encrypt, has changed this.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] HTTP/2, the latest version of HTTP protocol, allows unsecured connections in theory; in practice, major browser companies have made it clear that they would support this protocol only over a PKI secured TLS connection.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Web browser implementation of HTTP/2 including Chrome, Firefox, Opera, and Edge supports HTTP/2 only over TLS by using the ALPN extension of the TLS protocol.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] This would mean that, to get the speed benefits of HTTP/2, website owners would be forced to purchase SSL/TLS certificates controlled by corporations.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Currently the majority of web browsers are shipped with pre-installed intermediate certificates issued and signed by a certificate authority, by public keys certified by so-called root certificates.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] This means browsers need to carry a large number of different certificate providers, increasing the risk of a key compromise.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] When a key is known to be compromised, it could be fixed by revoking the certificate, but such a compromise is not easily detectable and can be a huge security breach.
[src:sigstore-signing/public-key-infrastructure] Browsers have to issue a security patch to revoke intermediary certificates issued by a compromised root certificate authority.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] When an artifact, blob, or container image is verified, the full potential of Sigstore to secure the software supply chain is achieved.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] The general verification format with the `cosign verify` command is as follows.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] We’ll use `user/demo` as our example image in the following commands and keyless signing where appropriate.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] The oidc-issuer for Google is https://accounts.google.com, Microsoft is https://login.microsoftonline.com, GitHub is https://github.com/login/oauth, and GitLab is https://gitlab.com.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] The following example verifies the signature on file.txt from user name@example.com issued by accounts@example.com.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] It uses a provided bundle `artifact.sigstore.json` that contains the certificate and signature.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] With container images, the signature and certificate are attached to the container.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] For blobs, the signature and certificate can be stored in a bundle file that is created at the time of signing.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] Either the bundle must be specified, or the individual signature and certificate must be specified.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] Signature payloads created by `cosign` included the digest of the container image they are attached to.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] By default, `cosign` validates that this digest matches the container during `cosign verify`.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] This will still verify the signature and payload against the supplied public key, but will not verify any claims in the payload.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] You can pass more than one image to `cosign verify`.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] Verify image with the provided certificate chain(s) and identity parameters (intended for “bring your own PKI” use cases).
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] The `--ca-roots` and `--ca-intermediates` flags are mutually exclusive with `--certificate-chain`.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] You can verify attestations on an image with `verify-attestation`.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] This will work with other flags, for example public key.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] You can also verify an attestation with the transparency log.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] These can be checked with matching `-a foo=bar` flags on `cosign verify`.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] When using this flag, **every** specified key-value pair **must exist and match** in the verified payload.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] The payload may contain other key-value pairs.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] If you lose the public key for some reason, you can re-export it from the private key.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] When verifying using the full `--kms <some provider>://<some key>` reference, you’ll make an API request to that service.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] This may require special permissions, depending on the service.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] For configuring Cosign to work with custom components, checkout the Configuring Cosign with Custom Components docs to find out how to achieve this.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] You can override the public good instance CA using the environment variable `SIGSTORE_ROOT_FILE` by running the following.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] There’s a new bundle format using bundle protobuf-specs that has a number of advantages over the previous bundle format: it supports offline verification, and includes additional information (like signed timestamps and attestations) in a single file.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] You can take existing signed material and make a new protobuf bundle with `cosign bundle create ...`.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] The Cosign `bundle` annotation contains a Signed Entry Timestamp (SET), which is conceptually similar to an SCT in a Web PKI system.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] The SET is a signed inclusion promise provided by the transparency log, which acts as a guarantee by the log that an element has been included in it.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] The SET can be verified with the logs public key and used to prove that an element is in the log without actually checking the log itself.
[src:sigstore-signing/verifying-verify] For more details on how the `bundle` annotation is formatted, review the Cosign spec.
